result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 11:37 AM Cases called: 20CF506 and 22CF200. Defendant Keegan A. Allsupp in court.  Attorney Claire M Edwards in court for Keegan A. Allsupp.  Attorney Jonathan Ross in court for State of Wisconsin. Waived reading of amended criminal complaint. Agreement recited by State. Court reviewed the rights & elements. Defendant pled no contest to counts 3 & 4 of 20CF506 of the amended information. Court found defendant guilty, entered judgment. 22CF200 dismissed and read in. Sentencing statements. Court withheld sentence, placed the defendant on probation for 24 months. Conditions of probation include: Complete an AODA assessment and follow through with any treatment recommendations. Undergo anger management counseling and comply with any treatment recommended. Submit DNA sample. Costs of $443.00 on count 3 and $243.00 on count 4. Court authorized the possibility of expungement upon successful completion of probation and all terms of probation. 6 days credit. 11:56 AM
